{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 21:43:16.971434", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\n\nExecutive summary\n- Network is partially configured: hosts in 10.0.0.0/24 and switches have management IPs in 20.0.0.0/24.\n- Critical anomaly: Open vSwitch (OVS) daemons are not running on all three OVS devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). As a result the dataplane/bridging/OpenFlow functionality is unavailable and inter-host forwarding across the fabric is impaired.\n- Localized faulty devices: leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1.\n- Probable root cause: openvswitch-switch service is inactive/stopped on each switch (service failure or not started). This causes OVS kernel/user components and the logical bridge (ovs-system / switch ports) to be down even though physical interfaces and management IPs exist.\n\nFindings and evidence\n1) Host addressing and basic interface state\n- host_1_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.1/24\n- host_1_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.2/24\n- host_2_1: eth0 = 10.0.0.9/24\n- host_2_2: eth0 = 10.0.0.10/24\n  (These hosts are up and have correct 10.0.0.0/24 addresses.)\n\n2) Switch management IPs present\n- leaf_1: has 20.0.0.5/24 on eth12 (management network)\n- leaf_2: has 20.0.0.6/24 on eth12\n- spine_1: has 20.0.0.1/24 on eth8\n  (Switches have management IPs assigned — management plane is configured.)\n\n3) Open vSwitch (OVS) processes/services are inactive\n- systemctl status (leaf_1): openvswitch-switch.service — Active: inactive (dead)\n- systemctl status (leaf_2): openvswitch-switch.service — Active: inactive (dead)\n- systemctl status (spine_1): openvswitch-switch.service — Active: inactive (dead)\n\n4) OVS bridge/kernel \"ovs-system\" and logical switch devices are down\n- get_host_net_config shows ovs-system and the logical bridge interfaces reported as state DOWN for the OVS root devices, while physical eth* interfaces attached to the OVS bridge show UP and assigned to the (down) ovs-system master. Example from leaf_1:\n  - ovs-system: state DOWN\n  - leaf_1 (logical device): state DOWN\n  - physical ports (eth0..eth11) show UP but are enslaved to ovs-system — with the OVS daemon down, switch dataplane behavior is not functional.\n\n5) Traffic counters (small TX from hosts)\n- Host interfaces show very few TX packets (e.g., TX packets = 6) while they have RX counts — consistent with hosts not being able to send traffic beyond local link (no forwarding) or the test pings not running. This is additional symptom consistent with bridges not forwarding.\n\nImpact / scope\n- All forwarding across the SDN fabric is affected because the underlying OVS switching plane is not active on the spine and leaf switches. Traffic between hosts attached to different leafs will not be forwarded by the fabric.\n- Management-plane (IP addresses) is present — so the nodes are reachable at IP level on the management NICs (subject to reachability), but OpenFlow/OVS dataplane is disabled due to the service being inactive.\n- The SDN controller (reported at 20.0.0.100 in the topology description) cannot manage the switches (even if it were reachable) while openvswitch-switch is not running.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Primary: openvswitch-switch service has stopped / is not running on the three OVS devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). This directly disables the OVS bridge(s) and OpenFlow pipeline.\n- Secondary possibilities (not proven by current data): service may have crashed due to an internal error, failed dependency, misconfiguration, or an intentional/accidental stop. There is no evidence in the gathered outputs about controller reachability or OVS log messages yet.\n\nRelevant extracted evidence (short excerpts)\n- leaf_1 systemctl status: \"openvswitch-switch.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n- leaf_2 systemctl status: \"openvswitch-switch.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n- spine_1 systemctl status: \"openvswitch-switch.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n- leaf_1 IP: \"inet 20.0.0.5/24 scope global eth12\"\n- leaf_2 IP: \"inet 20.0.0.6/24 scope global eth12\"\n- spine_1 IP: \"inet 20.0.0.1/24 scope global eth8\"\n- host_1_1 eth0: \"inet 10.0.0.1/24\"\n- host_1_2 eth0: \"inet 10.0.0.2/24\"\n\nNotes and suggested diagnostic verification (for information only)\n- The diagnosis relies on service status and interface state outputs collected. To confirm the exact cause of OVS stoppage (crash, intentional stop, failed dependency, filesystem/permission issue), review OVS service logs:\n  - journalctl -u openvswitch-switch (on leaf_1 / leaf_2 / spine_1)\n  - ovs-vsctl show (when OVS is running) and ovs-ofctl dump-ports-desc/ dump-flows (to inspect bridges/flows)\n- Verify management-plane reachability to controller (20.0.0.100) from switches to exclude a controller-related shutdown trigger:\n  - ping 20.0.0.100 (from the switches' management interfaces)\n- The reachability output previously collected returned \"unknown\" for many ping records — further targeted ping tests would help confirm data-plane reachability once OVS is restored.\n\nConclusion\n- The network has a clear and high-impact anomaly: OVS services are inactive on all OVS devices in the topology (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). This is the root cause of the dataplane/forwarding failure. Hosts and management IPs are configured, so the issue is at the switch software/service layer (OVS), not at basic interface addressing.\n\nIf you want, I can (a) collect openvswitch logs (journalctl) to find why the service is inactive, (b) run ovs-vsctl show (if service is started), or (c) run targeted ping/iperf checks once bridging is confirmed. Note: I will not perform any remediation actions unless you explicitly request them.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 24338, "output_tokens": 2398, "total_tokens": 26736, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 24064}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 960}}}
